accesses.location: On west shore; owned by city of Woodbury.  Multiple parking stalls for vehicles with trailers.

surveys.narrative: The northern pike population is very high, considerably higher than both state and local medians. Bluegills are a little below local medians but equal to statewide medians. The lake is reported to have nice size bass, with fair success rate of catch.

Black bullhead, yellow bullhead, yellow perch, and bluegill were found at below local median numbers. Northern pike, pumpkinseed, and hybrid sunfish were sampled at above local median levels. Largemouth bass are present. The May 1984 winterkill check showed very low bluegill numbers. Bluegill young-of-the-year are primarily progeny of pre-spawn adults stocked in June 1984. Golden shiner, green sunfish, and black crappie are present in low numbers.

Battle Creek Lake located in the City of Woodbury has public access via Shawnee Park on the west side of the lake. A surface use restriction of 10hp is imposed on outboard motors. A variety of native aquatic plant species were observed while motoring around the lake. An aeration system is present and operated by the City of Woodbury to prevent winterkill.Battle Creek Lake has a good population of northern pike with a good size range (17-32 inches). Other gamefish that were present but in low numbers were bluegill, black crappie and pumpkinseed. One largemouth bass was observed.

Battle Creek (Mud) Lake is a 103-acre, class 43 FiN lake located at the western edge of Woodbury just south of Interstate 94. The sport fish community consists of black crappie, bluegill, hybrid sunfish, largemouth bass, northern pike, pumpkinseed, walleye and yellow perch. The city of Woodbury operates a winter aeration system, a park (Menomini) that provides a fishing pier, and a park (Shawnee) that provides a boat access. Both park facilities offer paved trails, picnic tables, play structures, and off-road parking. For more information on amenities offered by Woodbury parks go to: http://www.ci.woodbury.mn.us/parks/parkinfo.html.

Largemouth bass, northern pike, and walleye were sampled in varying numbers. Although walleye have not been stocked in Battle Creek Lake, two age-5 walleyes, averaging 18.6 inches and 2.1 lbs, were sampled. Apparently migration from Tanners Lake is occurring on a limited basis. Walleyes have not been sampled in any of the previous surveys. Consistent with past sureveys, pike abundance (20.0/gill net) was high. Pike caught in gill net averaged 25.5 inches (range: 20.3 to 33.9 inches) and 4.0 lb, with 65% of the population exceeding 25 inches. Five largemouth bass averaging 11.2 inches and 1.2 lbs were also sampled. Inferences regarding bass population should not be made based on trap net catches. In order to properly sample the largemouth bass population, spring daytime electrofishing needs to be administered.

Panfish were in present in varying numbers. Bluegill numbers (15.42/trap net) were up from the 2004 survey (0.9/trap net). Seventy-seven trap netted bluegills averaged 6.3 inches with 58% exceeding 6.0 inches. The 2009 survey revealed trap net catches above 15.0/trap net for the first time since 1983. Consistent with past surveys, black crappie numbers were relatively low. Sampled crappies ranged between 4.9 and 8.0 inches. Two yellow perch were sampled in lone gill net in 2009 and no perch were sampled in 2004 assessment. Historical catches have ranged from 0 to 48 perch/gill net. No perch sampled in 2009 exceeded 8.0 inches. Hybrid sunfish (N=2) and pumpkinseeds (N=14) were sampled in relatively low numbers in both gill and trap nets. No sampled pumpkinseeds or hybrid sunfish exceeded six inches.

Black bullhead numbers (2.0/ gill net) were considerably lower than the gill net catches from the previous four surveys, where catches ranged from 65-170 per gill net. On the contrary, yellow bullheads were sampled in high numbers (9.0/gill net). Four golden shiners were also sampled in lone gill net. In addition, fourteen yellow bullheads, five common carp, and one brown bullhead were sampled in trap nets.

Northern pike populations were similar to previous investigations. Black bullhead and hybrid sunfish were above average abundance, but small in size. Bluegill were sampled in average numbers, but were also of small size. Yellow perch and yellow bullhead were taken in below average numbers.

Northern pike, black bullhead, and yellow perch were most abundant, all caught in numbers above their respective local median catch rates. The NOP sample was comprised of ages I, II, IV, and V and exhibited fast growth. Other species present but rare were white sucker, hybrid sunfish, green sunfish, pumpkinseed, bluegill, and black crappie. All of these centrarchids were small.

Battle Creek (Mud) Lake is a 103-acre, class 43 FiN lake located at the western edge of Woodbury just south of Interstate 94. The sport fish community consists of Bluegill, Hybrid Sunfish, Northern Pike, Pumpkinseed Sunfish. The City of Woodbury operates a winter aeration system, a park (Menomini) that provides a fishing pier, and a park (Shawnee) that provides a boat access. Both park facilities offer paved trails, picnic tables, play structures, and off-road parking. For more information on amenities offered by Woodbury parks go to: http://www.ci.woodbury.mn.us/parks/parkinfo.html.

Consistent with past surveys Northern Pike were sampled in above average numbers (9.0/gill net) but were below average in size. Pike caught in the gill net averaged 17.5 inches and 1.42 lb, with only one Northern Pike exceeding 25 inches. Panfish are present in low to average numbers. Bluegill numbers were down considerably from previous surveys with only one fish being observed. Pumpkinseed Sunfish are found in average abundance and size for lakes like Battle Creek. Hybrid Sunfish are present in low to average numbers. No sampled Pumpkinseeds or Hybrid Sunfish exceeded six inches. The overall low to average abundance of the various fish species found in Battle Creek Lake is likely due to the last two severe winters with some winter kill occurring in spite of the lake being aerated.

Northern pike, black bullhead, and yellow perch were quite abundant and bluegill adults (6655 planted spring 1989) were scarce. Northern pike were about average weight for this area and yellow perch were above average individual weight for the area and state-wide. Black bullheads were quite small. One largemouth bass weighing one pound was seen (none were seen during the electrofishing). Reproduction checks showed high numbers of perch and black bullheads, and fewer numbers of bluegills, pumpkinseeds, and black crappies.

The fish population consists of northern pike, black and yellow bullhead, yellow perch, and pumpkinseed, with very low numbers of largemouth bass, hybrid sunfish, bluegill, and black crappie present. Northern pike were abundant, with no fish captured weighing more than four pounds. Yellow perch, black and yellow bullhead were abundant but of small size. Pumpkinseed were present in low numbers, but size was small.

Golden shiner, black bullhead, northern pike, yellow perch, pumpkinseed, and hybrid sunfish were found at above local median levels. White sucker, green sunfish, bluegill and black crappie were found at below median levels.

Northern pike, black bullheads, yellow perch, and pumpkinseed sunfish were found at above median net catch numbers. Yellow bullhead, green, hybrid, and bluegill sunfish were found in numbers below state and local medians. No walleye, largemouth bass were sampled from the 1984 through 1986 stockings suggesting they may have died in the 1985-86 winterkill.
